Unlike Canada, individual states are responsible for organising federal elections in the US.
And in this spirit, most US governments have been declaring new laws since 2009 that make the election or registration process difficult.
This phenomenon has seen a boom following the November 2010 elections, during which 675 new Republican representatives have been added in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the right to vote in 41 states were submitted only in 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present photo ID and evidence of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws limit periods for elections ahead of time, invalidate the right to sign up on the electorate list on the day of the election, and withdraw the right to vote for citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required a photo ID on voters.
Indiana was the first state to implement this request.
The constitutionality of the Indian law was confirmed in 2008 by the U.S. Supreme Court.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this process to other states.
Over the past two years, they have supported proposals for such laws in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It should be noted that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal ID card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people of the age allowing to vote, do not own any photo ID issued by the government office of their state.
Furthermore, it does not have such an identity card of about five million new voters in 2012.
Moreover, the purchase of the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected mainly by young people, minorities and low-income people.
25% African-Americans, 15% income under $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
