Students who, as voters, are known for their attachment to democratic candidates, are not entitled to use their photo ID issued by their school in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs, who choose rather Republican candidates, to use the cards issued by these clubs in the elections.
Until 2004, no state had required proof of citizenship for elections.
Arizona introduced the first such request.
Since 2011, some 12 states have adopted laws that require voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly aim to limit the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two of the three Hispanics prefer a democratic party.
Republican legislation in 2011 supported laws in eight states that cancel voter registration on election day.
Moreover, they have limited the right of persons and groups to help voters who want to sign up.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the general elections in 2004, campaigns to register voters helped to register about 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% decrease in the entry of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican legislators then passed laws in the other five states aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general elections in Florida, African-Americans accounted for 33% of the voters who voted in advance, even though there were only 13% of African-American voters in that state.
It was the same with Hispanics.
