Another study, this time European, found a different mortality rate between patients who had undergone the examination and those who had not gone to it.
This study also showed that those who are not on the test have a 30 to 40% higher risk of metastases.
I therefore recommend an examination from 50 years of age or 40 years of age if your direct relative had prostate cancer.
African - American men are also a more vulnerable group.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is exposed.
There are aggressive types of cancer and species that are indifferent.
It is therefore necessary to explain correctly to the patient the level of risk of his type of cancer, to offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily to treat prostate cancer, which does not have an impact on life in the long term, and to focus on active disease surveillance in these cases.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not cured because their type of cancer is not aggressive and is not life-threatening.
Rather, we will suggest carrying out active supervision and offer them treatment in case of disease progression.
More and more often and with greater precision, we set criteria that help to decide which species to treat and which ones do not.
Still, I recommend that you pass the examination.
However, it is important to have an interview with a doctor and to determine whether it is appropriate to have an examination or not.
