Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is a view that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And it's the last particle that the standard model predicts - our best or "at least wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which, however, has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all data is still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, suppose it is the Higgs boson, because the risks of error appear to be small, and let's see what it is.
In this world, there is an unquestionable law under which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantical state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
Next, they divide the physics particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we will find decent citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow Pauli’s principle.
And at the other end, there are bosons, evil anarchists, who don't appreciate anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in Berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave unnoticed, and the "force particles" that spread large natural forces and with which the Higgs boson is probably related in some way.
It must be said, however, that these bosons are not as exotic animals as they might be thought.
If you read this article, it is due to a boson with unusual banality: photon, or "particle of light", which is the "bearer" of electromagnetic force.
When particles with electric charge accelerate or change their direction, they "interrupt" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into the pond.
This "interruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "power carriers".
More stable field
It's also with the Higgs boson, only with the difference that "interrupt" has to be another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it is necessary to achieve very high energy values in order to excite it, just like the frozen pond level, only a very large boulder will pick up.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with friendly bundles is a circle with a circuit of 27 km! - in order to be able to develop such energy.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field will be useful again to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
With the electromagnetic field, neither all particles nor all materials react.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the fridge.
And yet, with the Higgs field, all particles do not react: those that do have a mass, while others (such as the photon, let's look at it) do not.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what are all these researches for, what are they going to "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between observations and forecasts of SM.
Moreover, few physicists literally wish that they could be found, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, it does not bring any clarification of gravity (dense!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the space mass (again ouha!).
However, CERN has not yet found such contradictions.
Responses
The responses of these researches in Mr Novák's daily life can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
Behold: at the very beginning of the 1960’s, laser pioneers in Bell’s laboratories had no idea of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physics Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I already said - the laser was initially considered such a "toy for the lab".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application may result from all the tools surrounding research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle didn't plan it at all at first, now serves as the "eye" of all the digital cameras in the world and earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
Palliative care - The best way to get out of life... ? Le Devoir
Through his Commission for Decent Dying, Quebek recently became involved in a delicate issue about the end of his life.
