"They gave me five years to live and it's already seven," he says without emotion on his bed in the house for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"But it's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The illness has done its work: an immense weakness makes it impossible for him to take himself to the toilet or just to eat himself.
He looks down on a tasty - looking breakfast, and he agrees that we will help him eat.
He's brave and even smiles, talking to strangers who stop by, bringing him medication, offering him a bath.
Courage to an ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"A man learns throughout his life that men urinate standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
Going back to the child stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"Depends on the abilities of the man", says the psychologist.
In the opinion of a number of people dealing with palliative care, crucial moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients entering a home with palliative care, Victor-Gadbois, all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is at most three months of life.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses who take care of them do not provide so-called "healing" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die of "suffocation in full consciousness".
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good children," he adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in my life," she says, and then she allows us to put her breathing apparatus on.
Yet he is still looking forward to his last visit to his son from Italy in the following days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
That's what palliative care looks like when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, a single bed of palliative care covers 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize we're all gonna die someday.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it's a level of physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, he can be given a sip of brandy or pepsi, according to taste.
Diabetic patients no longer need to monitor their blood sugar levels.
And death is a part of everyday life here.
Last night, they were carrying a beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his late father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savardová, director of nursing services.
In Victor-Gadbois' home, days go by days, but they don't look like each other.
In addition to a 32 - year - old man who rejoices in his last encounter with his family thoroughly based on pillows while toasting to him in his honor, a tragically 36 - year - old man surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children dies after he has tried every opportunity to survive.
"There are always three to five beds for people with cancer under the age of 45 for six months," says Dr. Christiane Martel, concerned.
53% of the patients who come to home Victor-Gadbois come here from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick reach the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this crucial unavailability of medical care in Quebec that many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of the euthanasia and assisted suicide law.
Since October, the manifesto has been in circulation, signed by peaks in the field of palliative treatment, such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their disapproval of such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebek medical system is not powerful enough to provide access for all persons to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia can be carried out.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in an emergency room in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
They fear that patients should not be asked to be killed because they are not given appropriate care.
At the same time, many oncologists care for their patients until the last few moments, regardless of the adverse prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted stopping fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their treating physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative cunt team eased their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is certainly not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of Palliative Care in the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which will put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by impact or whether the sedative is administered permanently.
We can't pretend to ignore this part of the suffering.
A patient we can't relieve from pain will still have more access to palliative sedatives.
Sick people who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to provide me with euthanasia," it means "I want you to relieve my pain."
