How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user may choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The information set related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the validity of the transaction.
Furthermore, thanks to the file content, it is possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public book of current accounts distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is a file cutting phase; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they "cut" the whole thing.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other knots will easily check its accuracy.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to the string of all other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If the user wanted to pay twice the same money very quickly in a row (in 10 minutes), the network will only confirm one of both transactions - the other will be abandoned because each of them has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly shared by two, probably by the end of 2012.
