Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of this European Space Agency as the second member of the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of Agency projects over the years.
But Poland's journey to space began much earlier.
Before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were involved in space flights; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I will recall the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entry into Space.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) kept the listeners cool and after years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirscha Prize for his entry into space in France.
The remembered Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautism and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the dark side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925 a railway line was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was intended to be used to start a collision or to brake it.
The information about this drezín is only known from the period press.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to deal with missile missiles.
Research was provided by Komorka Techniki Ubrozenia in cooperation with Professor Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from preserved materials that research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, by the arrival of German troops, research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of the photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press and in the following year the work of Rakiet - Torpede powietrzna and rakietobombomba lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywoblocký came out.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) dedicated to all projects of military use of missile technology, which was coordinated by all the work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of its activity ended the start of the war.
Further work on cosmonautics appears after the war in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the Society is mentioned in the November issue of the 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, which contains four more comprehensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is designed to create a society that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronaut Federation (founded 1951) and already in the autumn, PTA has become a full member.
And in the following year, the first president of PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959) became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of a very successful weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should have been able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have reached up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, further developments were suspended in 1962.
Following the first RM rockets, the Meteor-1 rocket was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as two stages, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in size of space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, a space of 0.4 litre, a 0.34 litre Meteor-1B and a 0.62 litre Meteor-1C were available.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites within the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
