Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU, as in a globalised world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic formations, national economic systems, stand in permanent conflict with one another.
The cause is the principle of free trade and free, unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in labour prices, (major) price tensions occur.
Under that term, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the producer seeks to compete with the imports of cheap goods by "stimulating" the price of the competitor in order to attract more market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, it means for most entrepreneurs either to translate production abroad or to buy cheap goods there or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus the responsibility for unemployment produced by it, the social costs of the state are necessarily increasing.
The whole situation is heightened by the total reluctance of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in the pursuit of profit.
