Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained from voting in the decision on the adoption of Palestine.
According to an expert on US-European relations, Stephen Szabo, Berlin is balancing on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the proposal for Palestinian observer status in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he'll support America's position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
NATO finally pushed it through.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
Yes, that's right.
The reason is that it is changing its foreign policy, in the direction of the US-led policy, so to speak, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are settling in, but they are on their way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
Foreign policy, like they have in France or the UK.
What does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It shows the readiness to take on national interests as well as positions that are independent of the attitudes of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, namely export and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other powers, and therefore Germany has to protect its interests.
Did economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has a large market in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, they must be careful not to scare the public, but not even the elites in Arab countries.
Anyway, that's got to do with it.
But I wouldn't want to add too much importance to it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
However, this plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany’s relations with the US damaged when Germany abstained on both important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I think there is a great understanding of the German attitude in Europe and even in the US.
That is why I do not think that this was as dramatic a turning point as on the Libya issue.
Perhaps Germany will even earn some respect.
This indicates that it must be regarded as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, made it clear to veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of US internal policy.
I think that the Obama administration may have a considerable secretly understanding of the European position.
But, of course, as a result of the political situation there, this position cannot be held publicly.
I don't think the differences in opinion are at all as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not very happy with Netanyahu's policy.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US, on the one hand, and with the position of the most important partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that's what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans to have a coherent and united European policy, which is not currently happening.
So they can't be part of a wider line, and instead they have to push things forward from their own position.
That's what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does it even want to take the lead?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still unpleasant, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a larger role.
For example, when we look at the European crisis, every time Germany adopts a larger role, anti-German sentiments arise.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It is actually an old problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be acceptable to all the neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
The US's influence on European policy is now constantly falling, but the EU is currently not filling this vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more popular - c'est la vie!
