When you try to concentrate on a difficult or engaging task, the distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you do something boring, "like finding bad parts on the factory line, distracting music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he said, now we know that twisting and doodleing, which is often viewed as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom to fight and keep people physically more attentive.
"The research shows that children who are allowed to wriggle will learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We've all experienced boredom sometimes - the delay of my flight, the roaring speaker, especially the lengthy movie.
But some individuals have a better chance of being bored than others.
To help with the measurement of boredom, scientists in the 1980s developed the "Boredom Proneness Scale" (Bordom Proneness Scale).
The scale includes questions like: "Many things I have to do are repeated and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales scientists found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodonovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
Teenagers, however, are generally indifferent.
In 1991 Reed Larson, a professor for human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
