On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson stated that he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would now, 21 years later, be higher or lower.
But he said that he knew that "adolescents are the peak time for boredom", which is largely due to the fact that children and youth are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question, "Is boredom good for you?"
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, play gambling, or abuse addictive substances as a way to alleviate them.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodenovich, who studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Nude is a way of the brain to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the best thing to do.
If you are bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, watching television will only make you happy for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won't be bored anymore, but he won't learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate procedure is transferred from one situation to another," said the professor.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain greater self - control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of the reach of constant nagging of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We blame her for the need to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
