Hardest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, carriers in the area of Indonesian volcanoes gamble with their life and health as they withstand 70 kilos of sulphur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to rock to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulphur gases escape from the inside of the earth and when in contact with air, they go into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulphur that weigh up to 70 kilos together, it carries them on its shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, but it takes over 40 minutes for the exhausted carriers to rise at a turtle’s pace to balance and carefully reconsider their steps so that they do not slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed from the Kawah Ijen rocks years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are at the top, they take their way around the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in the circus, and they tirelessly carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is a company PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"Because it is normally carried 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip," Anto explains, who usually takes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and at the end he is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Even if it appears to be a negligible amount of inhuman effort, it's three times what he would have made in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day are paid for coffee collection, and the salary for fourteen days is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier who previously worked on Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as the sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto risked his life three times a day in Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur had already begun to take its toll on him, even though his face was protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases leaking out of the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than decent English.
This likable and intelligent young man of destiny could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at the hotel, and instead he does the work of a porter.
It shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and wakes up every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur continues to rise at night and its characteristic yellow colour changes into blue and glows in darkness.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto goes into the crater and lights his way with a small lamp attached to his helmet and bought it himself with his money.
About 400 carriers are carrying on the shoulders of a basket with sulfur from the bottom of the crater
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanised sulphur extraction because of cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such efforts.
In fact, they don't even get a share of 30,000 rupees (EUR 2.5) of the photo supplement, which, along with a ticket for 15,000 rupees (EUR 11.2), is selected by park rangers from tourists arriving to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for cattle, and not for humans," Madrusin, a robust 42-year-old carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assure us that he can work "as long as possible" because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm gonna die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings in the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in dense fumes coming out of the volcano, the miners are so determined that none of them complains that they suffer from serious diseases... but it is obvious from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and wounds on the shoulders caused by weight baskets.
At the age of 53, an unainic who balances his basket on his back can load just 50 kilos.
Each day he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which then three trucks take a steep route between the thicket to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik says, opening wide the mouth, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five sons he is the eldest, thirty years old, he also earns by mining sulphur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation - crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
