However, it admits that new standards lay down clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed.
Singapore is a city state.
Although these new rules could be aimed at increasing the birth rate of the nation, the interview with the Singaporeans working in the financial district in the city centre suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are always stressed, houses are expensive, as well as education, which is why many people postpone it," says the young clerk.
"Let the others have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time," says another, about 20 years old, young man.
Men and women refer to careers, stress and cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
