What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something that has a personal character or "a private life area that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption".
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would most certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years of age who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely of their own" on a personal level and as "user name and password" when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my biggest secret," says ten-year-old Jorge in an attempt to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing on FB.
I'm talking to my friends there, too.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that would mock anyone," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of José, a 14 - year - old, is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were directing him or asking him for an address or phone number.
"If they press me or demand me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading his recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend on the social network was blackmailed.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
According to José, the victim didn't check out of the account.
"You just activated a private regime."
Then explains a series of steps to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porrasová, an English teacher and a graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that children and adolescents need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform them.
He says: "The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic worker Marc Prensky, a graduate of teaching at Yale University and author of the article Digital Aboriginals and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that this is a complex subject, 'because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature to do so'.
Also, to be discreet about the surroundings, at a time when what they want most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do anything doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: Are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend's?
Do you know what other people publish about you?
When you identify the persons in the photos from the celebrations, did you ask these persons for permission?
And one more: do everyone always need to know what you're doing?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment the same way they do outside of it.
It's the same rules.
"Man is guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet and should be the same on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first - degree teacher, and educational advisor explains the need for children’s parents to carefully read social networking rules.
"If they understand every insidious thing, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences they may have of setting up an account on the Internet.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
The South American Summit ends and the Declaration of Lima has not been published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was announced and allegedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to a document signed at the sixth meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but representatives of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidential Offices, who at the beginning determined to publish the document after the summit, said that it would later be published on the Peruvian Government’s website.
They also stated that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in a few short press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, the video from the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "intimate meeting, sound transmission prevented".
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press speakers of some governments, who were present but not by the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document published during the negotiations was a list of participating presidents, which triggered the disapproval of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent out an e-mail to the media with a 'final statement' from the summit, but it is just a statement from President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (America del Sur-Países Arabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion, the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, even though the press was eagerly required.
On the official ASPA website it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure broadcasts for all journalists, but they completely prevented the flow of information.
The summit ended, inter alia, with a joint commitment from Chile and Peru to the adoption of a judgment of the Hague Court which addresses the dispute over the border between the two countries.
President Peru Ollanta Humala and President Chile Sebastian Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the arguments of both parties on Monday to discuss the dispute opened by Lima against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing in this international court today," said President Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts," he added and greeted President Humal with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they would submit to the decision of the International Court of Justice was published after Colombia had adopted the Bogot Pact this week, expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that had decided on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered this decision to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the withdrawal of then President Fernando Lug and did not attend the meeting.
The host President of Ollanta Humala was appointed to start the morning talks and conclude the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects between South American countries had been planned, with investments of $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries will take 'important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship for which residence agreements are being extended'.
He informed that actions were supported to improve 'cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap Internet in all parts of South America and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters'.
When Europe is in crisis, "it does not have a winning essence for economic consolidation (Latin America), but it is intended to increase our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport connections between various places in South America, especially rural and border areas... so that our countries will be better connected and create new economic links," the Peruvian president said in the reading.
He mentioned that five of these projects concerned Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from coast to Brazil, and the other two concerned a better connection with Ecuador, but did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to bring it back to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful area, which is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending a regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday, to discuss with respect the International Court of Justice’s ruling on the maritime border dispute that is being questioned by Bogota.
